statement:
Find the derivative of $y$ with respect to $x$ at the point
$P = (0,\pi)$ along the curve:

\begin{align*}\displaystyle{}\sin(x+y) = xy\end{align*}

sols:
Before we start, let's confirm that the point $(0,\pi)$ is indeed on the
line, as the statement suggests:

\begin{align*}
\sin(0+\pi) &= 0 \cdot \pi\\
\sin(\pi) &= 0\\
0 &= 0\end{align*}

The point is on the line. Next we want to find the derivative of the
function. We apply implicit differentiation and differentiate both
sides:

\begin{align*}
{\frac{{\rm d}}{{\rm d}x}} \sin(x+y) &= {\frac{{\rm d}}{{\rm d}x}} xy\\
\cos(x+y)\left(1+{\frac{{\rm d} {y}}{{\rm d}x}}\right) &= x{\frac{{\rm d} {y}}{{\rm d}x}} + y\end{align*}

The left hand side was obtained via the chain rule and the right hand
side was obtained via a product rule.

\begin{align*}
\cos(x+y) + {\frac{{\rm d} {y}}{{\rm d}x}}\cos(x+y) &= x{\frac{{\rm d} {y}}{{\rm d}x}} + y\\
{\frac{{\rm d} {y}}{{\rm d}x}}\cos(x+y) - x{\frac{{\rm d} {y}}{{\rm d}x}} &=  y - \cos(x+y) \\
{\frac{{\rm d} {y}}{{\rm d}x}}\left( \cos(x+y) - x\right) &= y - \cos(x+y) \\
{\frac{{\rm d} {y}}{{\rm d}x}} &= \frac{y - \cos(x+y)}{\cos(x+y) - x}\end{align*}

Substitute in the given point.

\begin{align*}
{\frac{{\rm d} {y}}{{\rm d}x}}(0) &= \frac{\pi - \cos(0+\pi)}{\cos(0+\pi) - 0} \\
{\frac{{\rm d} {y}}{{\rm d}x}}(0) &= \frac{\pi - (-1) }{(-1) - 0} \\
{\frac{{\rm d} {y}}{{\rm d}x}}(0) &= \frac{\pi + 1}{-1} = -(\pi+1)\end{align*}
